{"schemaVersion":1,"eventId":"evt-e68ddf23-c027-4f8b-a422-f25cf11e30c7","sequence":2475,"parentEventId":"evt-d8e1b8d1-8099-41fb-b586-c5cdc585f4a0","recordedAt":"2026-07-03T08:49:59.022Z","actor":{"id":"NJLaPrell@gmail.com","source":"system"},"command":{"name":"create-task","moduleId":"task-engine"},"kind":"task.created","payload":{"taskId":"T100798","initialStatus":"proposed","title":"Destructive SQLite migrations fire silently on DB open with no automatic backup","type":"defect"}}
{"schemaVersion":1,"eventId":"evt-c13c3756-6ba7-4fc9-8ef9-84c93b67184d","sequence":2476,"parentEventId":"evt-e68ddf23-c027-4f8b-a422-f25cf11e30c7","recordedAt":"2026-07-03T08:49:59.022Z","actor":{"id":"NJLaPrell@gmail.com","source":"system"},"command":{"name":"create-task","moduleId":"task-engine"},"kind":"task.updated","payload":{"taskId":"T100798","changedFields":["summary","risk","acceptanceCriteria","metadata"],"values":{"summary":"SQLite schema migrations (including the destructive v17→v18 and v38→v39 full table rebuilds, and the v37→v38 data-deleting migration) run automatically and silently the first time any command opens the planning database after a kit upgrade. There is no pre-migration backup, no user notification, and no rollback path. The 'workspace-kit upgrade' command backs up only text files, not the database.","risk":"high","acceptanceCriteria":["Destructive migrations (those that DROP tables or DELETE rows) trigger an automatic SQLite backup before executing","The backup path is logged to stdout so operators know where it was written","Alternatively, destructive migrations are gated behind explicit operator confirmation (not silent auto-run)","The 'workspace-kit upgrade' command either backs up the planning DB or documents clearly that it does not","Doctor output surfaces if the last successful backup predates the current schema version","New tests verify backup creation before destructive migration steps"],"metadata":{"issue":"Users can silently lose all task data when upgrading the kit, with no warning, no backup, and no recovery path.","supportingReasoning":"Reviewed src/core/state/kit-sqlite/planning-sqlite-kernel.ts. migrateV17ToV18() drops and recreates task_engine_tasks, task_engine_dependencies, and related tables. migrateV37ToV38() permanently deletes all wishlist_intake task rows. migrateV38ToV39() re-runs migrateV17ToV18(). All are called silently from prepareKitSqliteDatabase() on any writable open. The workspace-kit upgrade CLI path (src/cli.ts) only writes text file backups.","affectedFiles":["src/core/state/kit-sqlite/planning-sqlite-kernel.ts","src/cli.ts","src/cli/init-sqlite.ts"],"defectCategory":"data-safety","discoveryMethod":"code-review"}}},"expectedTaskVersion":1}
{"schemaVersion":1,"eventId":"evt-7a2fb8e9-1aaf-4815-b877-d2dcfc6f36ef","sequence":2477,"parentEventId":"evt-c13c3756-6ba7-4fc9-8ef9-84c93b67184d","recordedAt":"2026-07-03T08:50:31.734Z","actor":{"id":"NJLaPrell@gmail.com","source":"system"},"command":{"name":"create-task","moduleId":"task-engine"},"kind":"task.created","payload":{"taskId":"T100799","initialStatus":"proposed","title":"task-sync-hydrate silently destroys locally-only task data without merge or warning","type":"defect"}}
{"schemaVersion":1,"eventId":"evt-29e09c88-6cbe-4734-ba48-f9110a720519","sequence":2478,"parentEventId":"evt-7a2fb8e9-1aaf-4815-b877-d2dcfc6f36ef","recordedAt":"2026-07-03T08:50:31.734Z","actor":{"id":"NJLaPrell@gmail.com","source":"system"},"command":{"name":"create-task","moduleId":"task-engine"},"kind":"task.updated","payload":{"taskId":"T100799","changedFields":["summary","risk","acceptanceCriteria","metadata"],"values":{"summary":"When git-event-log canonical authority is active, running task-sync-hydrate (including the auto-hydrate triggered by the dashboard service worker) replaces the entire SQLite task projection with the contents of the remote git branch. Any tasks created or transitioned locally that have not yet been published to the git branch are permanently destroyed with no merge attempt, no confirmation prompt, and no mention in the command output that data was dropped.","risk":"high","acceptanceCriteria":["Before full-replay hydrate, the command detects and reports any locally-only tasks (present in SQLite but absent from the git branch)","Hydrate does not silently proceed past locally-only task detection without operator acknowledgment when in full-replay mode","The CLI output of task-sync-hydrate includes a count of tasks that will be dropped, if any","The dashboard worker's auto-hydrate either skips full-replay when local-only rows exist, or surfaces the drop count to operator-accessible status","task-sync-status output includes a locally-only task count so operators can detect the condition before hydrate"],"metadata":{"issue":"Operators and agents can silently lose work-in-progress task data during routine hydration, with no warning and no recovery path once the rebuild completes.","supportingReasoning":"Reviewed src/modules/task-engine/persistence/task-state-hydrate-runtime.ts and src/services/dashboard-service/task-sync-worker.ts. runRebuildTaskStateCache materializes a document from the git event stream and calls persistTaskStateProjectionDocument, replacing all SQLite task rows. The dashboard worker calls this path automatically. No pre-hydrate diff or local-only row detection exists.","affectedFiles":["src/modules/task-engine/persistence/task-state-hydrate-runtime.ts","src/modules/task-engine/persistence/rebuild-task-state-cache-runtime.ts","src/services/dashboard-service/task-sync-worker.ts"],"defectCategory":"data-safety","discoveryMethod":"code-review"}}},"expectedTaskVersion":1}
{"schemaVersion":1,"eventId":"evt-9dc5b03d-81c7-4baf-b5f6-f56071a0ecf6","sequence":2479,"parentEventId":"evt-29e09c88-6cbe-4734-ba48-f9110a720519","recordedAt":"2026-07-03T08:51:03.179Z","actor":{"id":"NJLaPrell@gmail.com","source":"system"},"command":{"name":"create-task","moduleId":"task-engine"},"kind":"task.created","payload":{"taskId":"T100800","initialStatus":"proposed","title":"workspace-kit upgrade backs up only config files — SQLite database unprotected before destructive migrations","type":"defect"}}
{"schemaVersion":1,"eventId":"evt-ad202d6a-3636-42fb-8dbf-4ee46e9aa039","sequence":2480,"parentEventId":"evt-9dc5b03d-81c7-4baf-b5f6-f56071a0ecf6","recordedAt":"2026-07-03T08:51:03.179Z","actor":{"id":"NJLaPrell@gmail.com","source":"system"},"command":{"name":"create-task","moduleId":"task-engine"},"kind":"task.updated","payload":{"taskId":"T100800","changedFields":["summary","risk","acceptanceCriteria","metadata"],"values":{"summary":"The 'workspace-kit upgrade' command prints a success message confirming that backups have been written, but it only backs up text files (manifest, profile schema, owned-paths, launcher). The SQLite planning database — which holds all task state, transition logs, audit traces, and module state — is not included in the upgrade backup. Operators who run 'upgrade' before a kit version change have a false sense of data safety.","risk":"high","acceptanceCriteria":["workspace-kit upgrade automatically invokes backup-planning-sqlite before completing, if a planning database exists","The upgrade output clearly reports the database backup path alongside the text file backup path","If the database backup fails, upgrade either aborts or warns prominently before the text file backup success message","Alternatively, upgrade documentation and CLI output explicitly warn that the database is not backed up and direct operators to run backup-planning-sqlite first","Doctor checks whether a backup exists for the current schema version and warns if not"],"metadata":{"issue":"The upgrade command gives operators false confidence that their data is safe. The most critical data store (SQLite) is not backed up, and destructive migrations will run silently on the next command.","supportingReasoning":"Reviewed src/cli.ts upgrade branch. Only writeFileWithBackupIfChanged calls exist — no database backup step. The backup directory listed in output contains only text files. Combined with the silent destructive migration behavior (T100798), upgrade followed by first DB open is a data loss window with no operator warning.","affectedFiles":["src/cli.ts","src/modules/task-engine/persistence/backup-planning-sqlite-runtime.ts"],"defectCategory":"data-safety","discoveryMethod":"code-review"}}},"expectedTaskVersion":1}
{"schemaVersion":1,"eventId":"evt-a19b95dc-e2d0-461a-af88-f355da5b7b88","sequence":2481,"parentEventId":"evt-ad202d6a-3636-42fb-8dbf-4ee46e9aa039","recordedAt":"2026-07-03T08:51:35.477Z","actor":{"id":"NJLaPrell@gmail.com","source":"system"},"command":{"name":"create-task","moduleId":"task-engine"},"kind":"task.created","payload":{"taskId":"T100801","initialStatus":"proposed","title":"Unhandled promise rejections in outbox publisher and dashboard task-sync worker can crash or silently degrade daemons","type":"defect"}}
{"schemaVersion":1,"eventId":"evt-7d8b87eb-f739-4b6d-9881-c4c372d3bde6","sequence":2482,"parentEventId":"evt-a19b95dc-e2d0-461a-af88-f355da5b7b88","recordedAt":"2026-07-03T08:51:35.477Z","actor":{"id":"NJLaPrell@gmail.com","source":"system"},"command":{"name":"create-task","moduleId":"task-engine"},"kind":"task.updated","payload":{"taskId":"T100801","changedFields":["summary","risk","acceptanceCriteria","metadata"],"values":{"summary":"The canonical event outbox publisher fires 'void this.runCycle().finally(...)' from a setInterval callback. The .finally() call does not catch rejections — if publishMarkedRows or any async step within runCycle() throws, the rejection propagates as an unhandled promise rejection. Similarly, the dashboard task-sync worker fires 'void this.runHydrateCycle()' from setImmediate and void calls, where executeHydrateCycle() wraps its body in try/finally but has no catch. Neither daemon registers a global unhandledRejection handler.","risk":"high","acceptanceCriteria":["runCycle() in canonical-event-outbox-publisher.ts has a top-level try/catch that logs errors and does not propagate them as unhandled rejections","executeHydrateCycle() in task-sync-worker.ts has a top-level try/catch, not only try/finally","Daemon process entry points (dashboard-service-daemon.ts, kit-run-daemon.ts) register a global unhandledRejection handler that logs and does not crash silently","All void async calls in setInterval, setImmediate, and similar fire-and-forget contexts attach .catch() handlers","Tests verify that a rejecting runCycle does not produce an uncaught rejection"],"metadata":{"issue":"Long-running daemon processes can be terminated or silently degraded by rejections in background timer callbacks, with no error logged and no operator visibility.","supportingReasoning":"Reviewed src/modules/task-engine/persistence/canonical-event-outbox-publisher.ts start() method and src/services/dashboard-service/task-sync-worker.ts executeHydrateCycle(). The .finally() on void runCycle() does not suppress rejections. executeHydrateCycle has try/finally but no catch, so any thrown error exits as an unhandled rejection from the void call site. No global handler exists in either daemon.","affectedFiles":["src/modules/task-engine/persistence/canonical-event-outbox-publisher.ts","src/services/dashboard-service/task-sync-worker.ts","src/services/dashboard-service/dashboard-service-daemon.ts"],"defectCategory":"reliability","discoveryMethod":"code-review"}}},"expectedTaskVersion":1}
{"schemaVersion":1,"eventId":"evt-77c30be0-224a-4dae-a255-642c7f956835","sequence":2483,"parentEventId":"evt-7d8b87eb-f739-4b6d-9881-c4c372d3bde6","recordedAt":"2026-07-03T08:52:06.902Z","actor":{"id":"NJLaPrell@gmail.com","source":"system"},"command":{"name":"create-task","moduleId":"task-engine"},"kind":"task.created","payload":{"taskId":"T100802","initialStatus":"proposed","title":"Dashboard service openStores() has a TOCTOU race that can open multiple SQLite handles to the same file","type":"defect"}}
{"schemaVersion":1,"eventId":"evt-586e001b-840d-4dc2-993c-cb44824d37ba","sequence":2484,"parentEventId":"evt-77c30be0-224a-4dae-a255-642c7f956835","recordedAt":"2026-07-03T08:52:06.902Z","actor":{"id":"NJLaPrell@gmail.com","source":"system"},"command":{"name":"create-task","moduleId":"task-engine"},"kind":"task.updated","payload":{"taskId":"T100802","changedFields":["summary","risk","acceptanceCriteria","metadata"],"values":{"summary":"DashboardSliceRefresher.openStores() checks 'if (!this.storesPromise)' then assigns 'this.storesPromise = await openPlanningStoresReadOnly(...)'. Because the assignment happens after an await, two concurrent calls that both observe storesPromise as null before either resolves will both proceed to open the planning database. The codebase explicitly warns that opening multiple handles to the same SQLite file in-process causes races. The extension client correctly uses a single-flight pattern for slice fetches; the dashboard service does not.","risk":"medium","acceptanceCriteria":["openStores() assigns storesPromise before the await so concurrent callers share one in-flight open","Two concurrent HTTP requests to /dashboard/refresh on a cold-start service result in exactly one SQLite handle being opened","Tests cover concurrent openStores() calls and verify single-open semantics","No multi-handle race warning is possible from the store-open path in the dashboard service"],"metadata":{"issue":"Concurrent dashboard refresh requests on service startup can open multiple SQLite handles to the planning database simultaneously, which the codebase documents as a race condition.","supportingReasoning":"Reviewed src/services/dashboard-service/slice-refreshers.ts openStores(). The TOCTOU window exists between the null check and the promise assignment across the await boundary. Contrast with extensions/cursor-workflow-cannon/src/views/dashboard/dashboard-pollers.ts which uses an inFlight Map assigned before await. SQLite dual planning store code explicitly notes multi-handle in-process risks.","affectedFiles":["src/services/dashboard-service/slice-refreshers.ts"],"defectCategory":"correctness","discoveryMethod":"code-review"}}},"expectedTaskVersion":1}
{"schemaVersion":1,"eventId":"evt-78d173f4-1712-456a-8bb6-8fba1536d94c","sequence":2485,"parentEventId":"evt-586e001b-840d-4dc2-993c-cb44824d37ba","recordedAt":"2026-07-03T08:52:39.764Z","actor":{"id":"NJLaPrell@gmail.com","source":"system"},"command":{"name":"create-task","moduleId":"task-engine"},"kind":"task.created","payload":{"taskId":"T100803","initialStatus":"proposed","title":"execFileSync calls to git and gh CLI have no per-invocation timeout — CLI and daemon can hang indefinitely","type":"defect"}}
{"schemaVersion":1,"eventId":"evt-5b69e6f1-4260-4e5f-a229-8a9c3ceec888","sequence":2486,"parentEventId":"evt-78d173f4-1712-456a-8bb6-8fba1536d94c","recordedAt":"2026-07-03T08:52:39.764Z","actor":{"id":"NJLaPrell@gmail.com","source":"system"},"command":{"name":"create-task","moduleId":"task-engine"},"kind":"task.updated","payload":{"taskId":"T100803","changedFields":["summary","risk","acceptanceCriteria","metadata"],"values":{"summary":"Multiple runtime files use execFileSync() to invoke the 'gh' CLI and spawn() to invoke 'git' without a timeout option. If the gh or git process hangs (network timeout, auth prompt, repository lock, etc.), the calling Node process blocks indefinitely with no recovery path. When this occurs inside the warm kit-run-daemon, all subsequent extension requests queue behind the hung call and the extension appears frozen until the daemon process is killed.","risk":"high","acceptanceCriteria":["All execFileSync calls to 'gh' include a timeout option (suggested: 30000ms or configurable)","All spawn-based git calls in phase-kickoff and staleness checks include a timeout with Promise.race or AbortController","When a gh or git call times out, the error is surfaced as a structured result (not a process hang)","The kit-run-daemon does not become unresponsive due to a hung subprocess","Tests cover the timeout path and verify the correct error code is returned"],"metadata":{"issue":"Network-hung or stalled git/gh processes can freeze the CLI and the extension warm daemon indefinitely, requiring operator intervention to kill the process.","supportingReasoning":"Reviewed wait-for-pr-checks-runtime.ts, harvest-delivery-evidence-runtime.ts, phase-kickoff-readiness-runtime.ts, and path-git-staleness.ts. execFileSync calls have no timeout property. spawn-based runGit() functions have no timeout or AbortController. Contrast with the policy.ts execFile call which does set a timeout. The kit-run-daemon serializes all requests, so one hung subprocess blocks all subsequent extension activity.","affectedFiles":["src/modules/task-engine/wait-for-pr-checks-runtime.ts","src/modules/task-engine/harvest-delivery-evidence-runtime.ts","src/modules/task-engine/derive-publish-artifacts-runtime.ts","src/modules/task-engine/release-status-runtime.ts","src/modules/task-engine/phase-kickoff-readiness-runtime.ts","src/modules/task-engine/kickoff/path-git-staleness.ts"],"defectCategory":"reliability","discoveryMethod":"code-review"}}},"expectedTaskVersion":1}
{"schemaVersion":1,"eventId":"evt-88c940a0-f982-4ed3-9334-94dba08f7993","sequence":2487,"parentEventId":"evt-5b69e6f1-4260-4e5f-a229-8a9c3ceec888","recordedAt":"2026-07-03T08:53:13.632Z","actor":{"id":"NJLaPrell@gmail.com","source":"system"},"command":{"name":"create-task","moduleId":"task-engine"},"kind":"task.created","payload":{"taskId":"T100804","initialStatus":"proposed","title":"Non-atomic file writes in memory-store and idea-store leave JSON files unrecoverable after a crash","type":"defect"}}
{"schemaVersion":1,"eventId":"evt-b466ca00-d60b-4401-afb3-ba5ddc98429b","sequence":2488,"parentEventId":"evt-88c940a0-f982-4ed3-9334-94dba08f7993","recordedAt":"2026-07-03T08:53:13.632Z","actor":{"id":"NJLaPrell@gmail.com","source":"system"},"command":{"name":"create-task","moduleId":"task-engine"},"kind":"task.updated","payload":{"taskId":"T100804","changedFields":["summary","risk","acceptanceCriteria","metadata"],"values":{"summary":"src/modules/project-memory/memory-store.ts and src/modules/ideas/idea-store.ts write their JSON files using fs.writeFileSync() directly to the target path. If the Node process crashes, is killed, or loses power mid-write, the destination file is left truncated or partially written, producing an unrecoverable JSON parse error on next read. The workspace status YAML export in the same codebase correctly uses an atomic tmp-file-then-rename pattern; these stores do not.","risk":"medium","acceptanceCriteria":["writeMemoryStore() writes to a temp file and renames atomically","The idea store write path writes to a temp file and renames atomically","A crash or SIGKILL mid-write does not produce a truncated or unparseable target file","readMemoryStore() handles a missing file gracefully (already does) and a corrupted file with a clear error, not a crash","Tests verify atomic write semantics (mock crash between write and rename leaves original intact)"],"metadata":{"issue":"Project memory and idea records are permanently corrupted and unrecoverable if the process crashes during a file write.","supportingReasoning":"Reviewed src/modules/project-memory/memory-store.ts writeMemoryStore() and src/modules/ideas/idea-store.ts. Both use direct fs.writeFileSync() to the target path with no atomicity. Compared against src/modules/task-engine/persistence/workspace-status-store.ts which uses tmp+rename correctly. The memory store also calls JSON.parse on read without a try/catch, so a corrupted file throws an unhandled error.","affectedFiles":["src/modules/project-memory/memory-store.ts","src/modules/ideas/idea-store.ts"],"defectCategory":"data-safety","discoveryMethod":"code-review"}}},"expectedTaskVersion":1}
{"schemaVersion":1,"eventId":"evt-318c4fe4-5878-46dd-a50a-34cc389d40a8","sequence":2489,"parentEventId":"evt-b466ca00-d60b-4401-afb3-ba5ddc98429b","recordedAt":"2026-07-03T08:53:46.070Z","actor":{"id":"NJLaPrell@gmail.com","source":"system"},"command":{"name":"create-task","moduleId":"task-engine"},"kind":"task.created","payload":{"taskId":"T100805","initialStatus":"proposed","title":"Dashboard HTTP service has no authentication, CSRF protection, or origin validation","type":"defect"}}
{"schemaVersion":1,"eventId":"evt-b0adf4a1-2b38-4873-b6a1-b3d98303db63","sequence":2490,"parentEventId":"evt-318c4fe4-5878-46dd-a50a-34cc389d40a8","recordedAt":"2026-07-03T08:53:46.070Z","actor":{"id":"NJLaPrell@gmail.com","source":"system"},"command":{"name":"create-task","moduleId":"task-engine"},"kind":"task.updated","payload":{"taskId":"T100805","changedFields":["summary","risk","acceptanceCriteria","metadata"],"values":{"summary":"The dashboard service HTTP server listens on 127.0.0.1 with no authentication tokens, no CSRF protection, and no request origin validation. Any local process running as the same user can send POST requests to /task-sync/flush, /task-sync/pause, /task-sync/resume, and /dashboard/refresh, affecting workspace sync state and triggering arbitrary slice refreshes. On shared machines or with SSH port forwarding, the attack surface extends to remote callers.","risk":"medium","acceptanceCriteria":["The dashboard service generates a random shared secret on startup and requires it on all POST requests (e.g. via a header or bearer token in the body)","The secret is written to runtime.json alongside the port so the extension can read it, but is not world-readable if file permissions allow","POST requests without the correct secret receive 401 or 403, not successful execution","Alternatively, the service uses a Unix domain socket instead of a TCP port, restricting access to the spawning user","GET endpoints (/health, /status, /dashboard/snapshot, /dashboard/slices/:name, /dashboard/events) may remain unauthenticated as they are read-only"],"metadata":{"issue":"Any local process can manipulate workspace sync state and trigger dashboard refreshes by sending unauthenticated POST requests to the dashboard service port.","supportingReasoning":"Reviewed src/services/dashboard-service/routes.ts and server.ts. All route handlers process requests without any credential or origin check. The port is advertised in .workspace-kit/dashboard-service/runtime.json. No CORS headers, no CSRF tokens, no auth middleware. POST /task-sync/pause and /task-sync/resume can halt background sync; POST /dashboard/refresh can trigger expensive DB reads with attacker-controlled slice names.","affectedFiles":["src/services/dashboard-service/routes.ts","src/services/dashboard-service/server.ts","src/services/dashboard-service/dashboard-service-daemon.ts"],"defectCategory":"security","discoveryMethod":"code-review"}}},"expectedTaskVersion":1}
{"schemaVersion":1,"eventId":"evt-b353cc31-d241-40e7-8266-ede5e31a8eba","sequence":2491,"parentEventId":"evt-b0adf4a1-2b38-4873-b6a1-b3d98303db63","recordedAt":"2026-07-03T08:54:19.335Z","actor":{"id":"NJLaPrell@gmail.com","source":"system"},"command":{"name":"create-task","moduleId":"task-engine"},"kind":"task.created","payload":{"taskId":"T100806","initialStatus":"proposed","title":"Outbox publisher Math.min version merge generates spurious task-state-publish-task-conflict for sequential same-task mutations","type":"defect"}}
{"schemaVersion":1,"eventId":"evt-76948a29-2caa-41dd-937a-c657aaaefd4c","sequence":2492,"parentEventId":"evt-b353cc31-d241-40e7-8266-ede5e31a8eba","recordedAt":"2026-07-03T08:54:19.335Z","actor":{"id":"NJLaPrell@gmail.com","source":"system"},"command":{"name":"create-task","moduleId":"task-engine"},"kind":"task.updated","payload":{"taskId":"T100806","changedFields":["summary","risk","acceptanceCriteria","metadata"],"values":{"summary":"When the canonical event outbox batches multiple pending events for the same task, mergeExpectedTaskVersions() uses Math.min to combine their expectedTaskVersion values. For sequential mutations on a single task (e.g., task created at version 0, then transitioned at version 1), the batch uses version 0 as the expected version for both events. When the batch is published against the remote git branch — which already reflects the creation event — the version check sees version 1 on the remote and 0 in the batch, producing a task-state-publish-task-conflict with no concurrent writer involved.","risk":"medium","acceptanceCriteria":["Sequential mutations to the same task do not produce task-state-publish-task-conflict when batched in the outbox","The outbox publisher handles same-task sequential events correctly, either by publishing in sequence order per task or by deriving the correct expectedTaskVersion per event in the batch","Concurrent mutations to the same task from separate writers still produce the correct conflict signal","Tests cover the sequential same-task batch case and verify successful publish without false conflict","The fix does not regress the concurrent-writer conflict detection behavior"],"metadata":{"issue":"The outbox publisher's version batching logic treats sequential mutations to the same task as concurrent conflicts, causing publish failures and requiring manual operator intervention to clear stuck outbox rows.","supportingReasoning":"Reviewed src/modules/task-engine/persistence/canonical-event-outbox-publisher.ts mergeExpectedTaskVersions(). It iterates all rows and calls Math.min on the version for each taskId. For two rows where task A was at version 0 (creation) then version 1 (transition), the merged expected version is min(0,1)=0. The remote branch will reflect version 1 after the creation event lands, so the transition event's batch will conflict. No concurrent writer is required to reproduce this.","affectedFiles":["src/modules/task-engine/persistence/canonical-event-outbox-publisher.ts","src/modules/task-engine/persistence/canonical-event-outbox-store.ts"],"defectCategory":"correctness","discoveryMethod":"code-review"}}},"expectedTaskVersion":1}
